<h2>Syllabus</h2>

This is a first course in real analysis.  We will study in a rigorous fashion the the real numbers and functions on the real numbers.  Students will gain practice in writing proofs which are rigorous and clear.
<br>
<br>

<b>Textbook</b>: The textbook for this course is <i>Elementary Analysis: The Theory of Calculus</i> by Kenneth A. Ross.  I may also draw material from Rudin's <i>Principles of Mathematical Analysis</i>, though this text is not required.  I will also post lecture notes.
<br><br>
<b>Lecture</b>:  Since this is a relatively small class, I want to keep the lectures fairly informal.  I hope that students will ask questions and that the atmosphere will be a bit more conversational -- more like your experiences in discussion versus in lecture.  I am not worried about pace; if I get too behind, I can make it up during discussion.<br><br>I will not lecture directly from the textbook, and I may not follow the order.   In addition to attending lecture, students are expected to read at least some of the textbook to fill in the gaps.  I will try to point out where in lecture I omit details.
<br><br>

<b>Grades</b>: 20% homework, 40% for each of the exams.  If you score higher on the final exam than the midterm, I will use your final exam grade in lieu of that midterm grade.  Further, style will be a factor in grading for this course.  A good proof buried in nonsense will not be awarded full credit.
<br><br>

<b>Exercises</b>: On the schedule, for each lecture, I will post some exercises from the book.  These are not too difficult but you are highly encouraged to do them.  They will not be collected, nor graded.<br><br>

<b>Homework Policy</b>: Homework will be collected every Monday except the first day of class and including exam weeks, for a total of seven assignments.  There are no dropped assignments.  You may work with other students but your writeup must be entirely in your own words.  Your homework is expected to be written legibly or typed, and stapled when handed in.  I will allow the grader to deduct points for illegible or inconvenient homework.
Homework will be graded on correctness as well as clarity of exposition.  Not every homework problem will be graded: I will choose at random a subset of the homework problems to comment and grade.
<br><br>

<b>Homework Writeup</b>: Each student will be responsible for a write-up of one problem over the course of the semester.  What I mean by this is that you will be contributing one problem to your class' answer key.  You will turn in your homework along with the other students on Monday.  I will give you a photocopy of that problem with extended comments for you to revise your solution.  You must then turn in a revised solution by Wednesday.  Doing the writeup with due diligence will result in a full score.  This write-up will account for the equivalent of one homework assignment, so it is a pretty big part of your grade.<br><br>

<b>Midterms, Final</b>: The midterm will be on 7/24/2014.  The final exam will be on <strike>8/14/2014</strike> <b>8/13/2014</b>.  <strike>All exams are on Thursdays</strike>; class will be extended into section on exam days so that students have two hours to take the exam.  All exams will be open book in the sense that you can use the official textbook but not other resources (including the lecture notes).  <strike>YOU MUST PURCHASE AND BRING YOUR OWN STANDARD BLUE EXAM BOOKLETS TO THE EXAM.</strike>  <b>I am no longer requiring blue books, but it may be a good idea to blank scrap paper to the exam.</b>
<br><br>

<b>Section</b>: Section will be an opportunity for students to ask questions.  Daily attendence is optional.  It is the responsibilty of the student to come to section armed with questions.  My suggestion is to attempt the suggested exercises and ask about those.
<br><br>

<b>Forum</b>: A <a href="http://piazza.com/berkeley/summer2014/math104chen/home">Piazza forum</a> has been created for this class.  This is a good way to get in contact with your fellow students.<br><br>

<b>Miscellany</b>: Incomplete grades will be given only for documented medical or personal emergencies.  Workload from other courses or employment are not grounds for an incomplete grade.  All cases of academic dishonesty will immediately be referred to Professor Haiman.  Students who require special circumstances should attain them through the Disabled Students' Program.

<br><br>
<b>Advice</b>: For some students this will be their first exposure to rigorous mathematics.  The following is some personal advice based on my own experiences -- they are by no means perscriptive nor authoitative and the student is encouraged to "find their own way" to understand mathematics.  That being said, the communication of mathematics and one's inner intuition must be done in a clear and rigorous way.  The following is entirely my opinion.  I am sure you can find someone who disagrees with me, and they're probably right.<br><br>

On reading math: I often find it helpful to have many examples in mind, one because they are concrete and two because they give me a place to start when faced with a question for which I do not know the answer.  When faced with a theorem or definition statement with many conditions, I find it helpful to ask what happens if I remove a condition -- can I come up with a counterexample?
<br><br>
On writing proofs: proofs must be rigorous.  However there is a balance between inclusion and omission which is difficult to characterize and must be learned.  Proofs should also be organized neatly on the page and separated into paragraphs in accordance to usual practices in essay writing.  Remember -- you're not just proving it to yourself, but to the reader as well.  This is all easier said than done, but one must at least keep it in mind.
<br><br>
On reading proofs, I've found two pitfalls at opposite extremes: reading and justifying the proof line-by-line on one extreme and coming up with a "big picture" argument which ignores the details on the other.  In reality we need to be able to do both: we need to remember the general idea of an argument but have internalized enough of the details to really understand it.  For me, it sometimes helps to try the proof on a few examples.  Proofs are often written in a logically sequential format, which is not really the way I think.  For me, if I really want to understand something, it's more useful to write down a "skeleton" of a proof where I make unproven claims and then fill in the proofs of such claims later.
